BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:E4-Z-T6yahULjLr6iE91I
SUMMARY:Beyond Mysticism: The Modern Northwest
DTSTAMP:20260401T023628Z
DTSTART:20260402T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:image: Drift No. 2\, 1936\, Malcolm M. Roberts\, American\, 191
	3-1990\, tempera on board\, 25 1/2 x 20 5/8 in.\, Seattle Art Museum\, Eug
	ene Fuller Memorial Collection\, 37.103\, © Malcolm M. Roberts\, photo: Sc
	ott Leen.\n\nInspired by the region’s natural beauty and rapidly changing 
	city\, this exhibition showcases artists who told the raw story of Seattle
	 in the 20th century. By sharing the Pacific Northwest’s perspective throu
	gh trending art styles—including Social Realism\, Surrealism\, and Abstrac
	t Expressionism—these artists offered a unique take on Modernist art and c
	hallenged the “mystic” label ascribed to their works.\n\nSpearheading the 
	movement were local icons Mark Tobey\, Kenneth Callahan\, Guy Anderson\, a
	nd Morris Graves—but the range and breadth of Pacific Northwest art goes b
	eyond the “Big Four” of the Northwest School. Featuring more than 150 piec
	es\, this exhibition showcases works that investigate the complexities of 
	daily life in the region. Whether applying an ecocritical lens or producin
	g dreamy and uncanny visuals\, these artists expressed the duality of the 
	natural world and city life to warn of the environmental and social impact
	s of industrialization.\n\nFrom Malcolm Roberts to Kenjiro Nomura\, learn 
	how Northwest artists applied their regional perspective to broader artist
	ic developments to create a new form of American Modernism.\n\nThe exhibit
	ion is accompanied by a fully illustrated catalogue authored by Theresa Pa
	panikolas\, SAM’s Ann M. Barwick Curator of American Art.\n\nhttps://seato
	day.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-modern-northwest/183
	08126/2026-04-02T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-mode
	rn-northwest/18308126/2026-04-02T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:qFnT20JxjWQmqcgZHjfqs
SUMMARY:March Madness Watch Party at Five Iron Golf - Seattle Capitol Hill
DTSTAMP:20260401T023628Z
DTSTART:20260402T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Five Iron Golf is your College Basketball HQ this March! Gather
	 your crew and book 1–2 simulator bays for up to 12 people \\(6 people per
	 bay\\) for a bracket-busting watch party experience. Enjoy all-day TV cov
	erage of college basketball alongside cutting-edge golf and multisport sim
	ulators\, a locally-inspired menu\, and custom beverage packages.\n\nBook 
	your watch party for March 19 or 20 and you'll automatically be entered to
	 win a 20-person happy hour with drinks and appetizers — a $1\,000 value!\
	n\nGroup packages can include reserved event space\, team-specific décor\,
	 a dedicated staff member\, full-screen and/or picture-in-picture viewing\
	, a customizable menu\, beverage packages\, free club rentals\, multisport
	 simulators\, and table games. Select the "Small Event" option at booking 
	to ensure simulator bays are placed side-by-side. Availability of select f
	eatures varies by location.\n\nPromotions:\n\nHappy Hour – "It's 5i o'Cloc
	k Somewhere" \\(Monday–Friday\, 3–6 PM\\)\n\nEnjoy $5 bottomless boneless 
	wings\, $10 bottomless bone-in wings\, $5 select beers/cans/cocktails\, $5
	 dips \\(guacamole\, hot honey ricotta\, hummus\\)\, half-off pizzas\, and
	 $5 featured shots. Dine-in only at participating locations\; simulator re
	ntal may be required.\n\n5i After Dark – "Swing In\, For Less"  \\(Sunday–
	Thursday 9 PM to close | Friday–Saturday 10 PM to close\\)\n\nFeatures $29
	/hr simulator rentals plus the same great food and drink specials as Happy
	 Hour\, with wings priced per dozen rather than bottomless. Dine-in only a
	t participating locations\; simulator rental may be required.\n\nhttps://s
	eatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/march-madness-watch-party-at-five-iro
	n-golf-seattle-capitol-hill/18268907/2026-04-02T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All 
	Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/march-madness-watch-party
	-at-five-iron-golf-seattle-capitol-hill/18268907/2026-04-02T00
LOCATION:Five Iron Golf - Seattle Capitol Hill\, 1525 11th Ave Suite 100\, 
	Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT12H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:Bu_SFCf1xnB3Hd0wuwnSK
SUMMARY:Eric-Paul Riege at Burke Artist Studio
DTSTAMP:20260401T023628Z
DTSTART:20260402T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:To celebrate the opening weekend of Eric-Paul Riege: ojo|-|ólǫ
	́\, visit the artist offsite at the Burke Artist Studio\, located in the N
	orthwest Native Art Gallery at the Burke Museum\, just a few blocks from t
	he Henry. As part of Free First Thursday at the Burke\, visitors will have
	 the chance to watch the artist at work and speak with Riege about his pro
	cess. ojo|-|ólǫ́ is based on Eric-Paul Riege's material research and enga
	gement with the Navajo collections held by the Burke Museum\, as well as t
	he Brown University's Haffenreffer Museum of Anthropology. The resulting n
	ew body of work is informed by ancestral knowledge and traditions containe
	d within Indigenous objects\, and which aims\, in part\, to redress practi
	ces of cultural dispossession by museums and other institutions. Bio Eric-
	Paul Riege \\(Diné\\) is a weaver and fiber artist working in collage\, du
	rational performance\, installation\, woven sculpture\, and wearable art. 
	Using weaving as both means and metaphor to tell hybrid tales that interla
	ce stories from Diné spirituality with his own interpretations and cosmolo
	gy\, he understands his artworks as animate and mobile. His practice pays 
	homage and links him to generations of weavers in his family who aid him i
	n generating spaces of sanctuary. Riege's recent solo exhibitions include 
	iiZiiT \\[3\\]: RIEGE Jewelry \\+ Supply at Canal Projects\, New York \\(2
	025\\)\, Hammer Projects: Eric Paul Riege at the Hammer Museum\, Los Angel
	es \\(2022-2023\\)\, and Hól ́ǫ-it xistz at the Institute of Contemporary 
	Art Miami \\(2019\\). His recent group exhibitions include the 24th Bienna
	le of Sydney in Australia \\(2024\\)\, Indian Theater: Native Performance\
	, Art\, and Self-Determination \\(2023\\)\, Prospect.5 Triennial in New Or
	leans \\(2022\\)\, and the Toronto Biennial of Art \\(2022\\). He holds a 
	BFA in Art Studio and Ecology from the University of New Mexico in Albuque
	rque. His work is collected by Forge Project and ICA Miami\, among others.
	 He is represented by Bockley Gallery \\(MN\\) and STARS Gallery \\(CA\\).
	 Riege is a member of the Charcoal Streaked Division of the Red Running In
	to the Water clan. He was born and is based in Na'nízhoozhí \\[Gallup\, Ne
	w Mexico\\].\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/eric-paul-ri
	ege-at-burke-artist-studio/18292527/2026-04-02T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All E
	vents
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/eric-paul-riege-at-burke-
	artist-studio/18292527/2026-04-02T00
LOCATION:Henry Art Gallery\, 15th Ave NE & 41st St\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT5H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:glNUc6YNiE_CxJFgzj29s
SUMMARY:TADAIMA: I'm Home
DTSTAMP:20260401T023628Z
DTSTART:20260402T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:After more than 80 years\, a treasured collection returns “home
	” to Seattle’s Japanese American community. In 1942 dozens of traditional 
	Boys’ and Girls’ Day dolls were entrusted to Bailey Gatzert Elementary Sch
	ool by Japanese American families facing forced incarceration. Most were n
	ever reclaimed after the war. Artist Miya Sukune uses recent research in M
	OHAI’s collection\, as well as interviews with Japanese American survivors
	 and their descendants\, to create an installation called “Tadaima\,” mean
	ing “I’m home.”\n\nTADAIMA: “I’m Home!” Bringing Seattle’s Girls’ and Boys
	’ Day Dolls Home reconnects the dolls with their traditional role of prote
	cting and blessing children. It invites visitors to celebrate the resilien
	ce\, memory\, and enduring traditions of the Japanese American Community.\
	n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-02T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-02T00
LOCATION:Museum of History and Industry\, 860 Terry Ave N\, Seattle\, Seatt
	le\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:WLJBKi5M2NWXGUqrd7cMi
SUMMARY:Samantha Yun Wall: What We Leave Behind
DTSTAMP:20260401T023628Z
DTSTART:20260402T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Samantha Yun Wall’s new paintings use overlapping silhouettes o
	f female figures as portals to unknown spaces and different temporal realm
	s. Impetus for the new body of work is a Korean folk tale in which the Pas
	que flower is symbolic of a grandmother who passed away without the loving
	 care of her grandchildren. It is a story of melancholy\, loss\, and remem
	brance. The delicate hair on the flower’s stem differentiates it\, and the
	 artist gives the plant a surreal aspect in some of her paintings\, replac
	ing the flower’s center with a watchful eye.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.c
	om/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we-leave-behind/18026187/2026-0
	4-02T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we
	-leave-behind/18026187/2026-04-02T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
